Mr. INGRAM. When I was interrupted a moment ago, I said that I had but few words to add; but since the speech made by the Minister of Finance, I have con— cluded to offer some further remarks, espe— cially in reply to those made by him con— cerning the election recently held in Edmon- ton. For some weeks past this House has resounded time and again with challenges to the government to open constituencies in order to test public feeling in the country. Hon. members on this side have been free in making these challenges. and the govern— ment could not ‘muster up suﬂicient courage to accept them. But at last, after due con- sideration, I presume, they thought it prob» ably wise to appoint a Minister of the 111s terior. Rumour had it that the constituency of West Assiniboia was to have been opened for the purpose of testing public opinion ;. but for some reason or other unknown to members of the opposition, the government saw ﬁt to change their opinions at the eleventh hour and decided to open up the constituency of Edmonton instead. What I want to draw the attention of the people of this country to is this fact, that the Con- servative party were asked to enter into a contest in a district which, as nearly as I can ﬁgure it out. comprises an area of 426 miles by 210 miles.
